<DOC><DOCNO> AP890113-0121 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-13-89 1405EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Britain-ComputerVirus 2ndLd-Writethru a0601 01-13 0288</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Britain-Computer Virus, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0601,0292</SECOND><HEAD>`Friday the 13th' Virus Strikes Computers</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf, `A spokesman ...,' to CORRECT that IBM spokesmansaid virus affected computers made by IBM, sted at IBM location.</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A ``Friday the 13th'' computer virus struckpersonal computers in Britain on Friday, wiping out program filesand annoying businesses, a computer expert said.   Hundreds of personal computer users found the virus wasprogrammed to delete files on Friday the 13th, said Alan Solomon,managing director of S and S Enterprises, a data recovery center inChesham.   The virus, which might be a new species, has been slowing downcomputers made by International Business Machines Corp. andcompatible models, said Solomon, who also is chairman of an IBMpersonal computer users group.   Telephone lines to the center were busy with calls for help frombusinesses and individuals whose computers were struck by the virus,he said.   ``It has been frisky and hundreds of people, including a largefirm with over 400 computers, have telephoned with their problems,''he said.   A spokesman for IBM in Portsmouth, who asked not to beidentified, confirmed that the virus had wiped out files in personalcomputers made by IBM and compatible machines. He said he didn'tknow whether larger computers were affected.   In the United States, several computer-security experts saidtoday they had not heard any reports the virus had crossed theAtlantic.   Solomon said his company would try to figure out how the virusoperates and then attempt to kill it. The identity of the hacker whodevised the virus might never be known, he said.   ``It is just a pesky nuisance and is causing a lot of problemstoday,'' Solomon said.</TEXT></DOC>